ol.li:
For the HTML5 based transformation, start by disabling the automatic table and figure
        numbering. 

Remove the labels from the table titles. In your customization
              CSS:.table--title-label,
.fig--title-label {
  display:none;
}

*[class ~= "listentry/number"],
*[class ~= "listentry/prefix"]{
	display:none;
}		


Make the links use only the title text. Set the transformation parameters:
              args.tablelink.style=TITLE and
              args.figurelink.style=TITLE.

Reset the counters at the start of each chapter 
          *[class ~= "topic/topic"][is-chapter]{
  counter-reset:page 1 section1 tablecount figcount !important;
}  				
          The counter-reset property is not additive, it will simply overwrite the existing
            definitions. You need to preserve the other counter resets that come from the built-in
            CSS, like the section1 counter.

Increment the table counter at each table, and the figure counter at each figure.
          *[class ~= "topic/table"]{
  counter-increment: tablecount;
}  				
*[class~="topic/fig"] {
  counter-increment: figcount;
}

Use the chapter and table/figure counters in the titles. 
          *[class ~= "topic/table"] > caption:before {
  content: "Table " counter(chapter) "-" counter(tablecount) "  ";
} 				
*[class ~= "topic/fig"] > figcaption:before {
  content: "Figure " counter(chapter) "-" counter(figcount) "  ";
}

Use the chapter and table/figure counters in the links. 
          *[class ~= "topic/xref"][type="table"],
*[class ~= "placeholder/tablelist"] *[class ~= "listentry/entry"]:before{
  content: "Table " 
  target-counter(attr(href), chapter, decimal) 
  "-" 
  target-counter(attr(href), tablecount, decimal) "  ";
}

*[class ~= "topic/xref"][type="fig"],
*[class ~= "placeholder/figurelist"] *[class ~= "listentry/entry"]:before {
  content: "Figure " 
  target-counter(attr(href), chapter, decimal) 
  "-" 
  target-counter(attr(href), figcount, decimal) "  ";
}
          The listentry/entry are the entries from the DITA bookmap
              figurelist and tablelist
            elements.

          The labels provided by this sample CSS are not localized. You should use the
              :lang selector to provide labels for other languages, if
            applicable.*[class ~= "topic/xref"][type="table"]:lang(fr) {
  content: "Tableau " .....
  .....
}
